{"key":"post-9042585","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9042585</id>\n<content>Actually, mushroom mycelium prefers an acid pH.&amp;nbsp; The problem is that trichoderma also prefers an acid pH, thus we raise the pH of our casing layers, because as said above, the mushroom mycelium is more tolerant.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If you don't have a way of measuring pH, simply use 1 teaspoon of hydrated lime per cup of peatmoss in your casing.&amp;nbsp; That will get you in the ballpark of pH 8.&amp;nbsp; If you have test strips or a good meter, you can take it to 8.5 if you want, but be sure to measure it an hour after adding the lime.&amp;nbsp; The pH will swing WAY high during the first half hour, and then come back down and stabilize.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>9042558</prev>\n<first>9042118</first>\n<last>9042585</last>\n<when>1223409761</when>\n<utime>10/07/08 11:02 PM</utime>\n</post>"}